08:34:29","updated":"2022-01-06 20:08:32","type":"photo","description":"Charles Warriax and Simeon Oxendine, both members of the Lumbee tribe of North Carolina, pose triumphantly with a KKK flag they seized during the Battle of Hayes Pond.\n\nIn 1958, the Ku Klux Klan tried to hold a rally and cross burning in the heavily Native American town of Maxton, North Carolina, to intimidate the local population and recruit more members. Instead, the Klansmen were outnumbered 10 to 1 by the 500 armed members of the Lumbee tribe, many of whom had fought in World War II, who showed up to meet them. For several minutes, the field where the rally was to be held turned into a battleground. \n\nGunfire erupted everywhere, Klansmen fled into the woods, and the Lumbee captured the KKK's banner, cross, and even their PA system, all of which they kept in celebration of their victory.\n\nWithin days, the story of the Battle of Hayes Pond made national news and even garnered a three-page spread in Life In the animal and bird world there existed a brotherly feeling that kept the Lakota safe among them.\n\nThe animals had rights -- the right of human protection, the right to live, the right to multiply, the right to freedom, and the right to our indebtedness -- and in recognition of these rights the Lakota never enslaved an animal and spared all life that was not needed for food and clothing.\n\nThis concept of life and its relations was humanizing and gave to the Lakota an abiding love. It filled their being with the joy and mystery of living; it gave them reverence for all life; it made a place for all things in the scheme of existence with equal importance to all.\n\nFrom Wakan Tanka, the Great Spirit, there came a great unifying life force that flowed in and through all things -- the flowers of the plains, blowing winds, rocks, trees, birds, animals... Thus all things were kindred, and were brought together by the same Great Mystery.\"\n\n~Chief Luther Standing Bear~\n\nPhoto by Shane Pilgrims did not sit down for a big turkey dinner and it was not an event that the Wampanoag knew about or were invited to in advance. In September/October 1621, the Pilgrims had just harvested their first crops, and they had a good yield. They “sent four men on fowling,” which comes from the one paragraph account by Pilgrim Edward Winslow, one of only two historical sources of this famous harvest feast. Not having my husband home, and not physically being in an office with my coworkers left me feeling lonely and isolated. I had no family around and most of the friends were not married and didn’t have kids, so I was finding it difficult to find support .Looking in the mirror I felt like I couldn’t recognize myself anymore because I was no longer the person I was before motherhood, every day started to feel like the same day was just repeating itself over and over again. Two months ago, in September of 2021 I joined a moms app honestly I was super hesitant to join. Just go out more” or “so, is it like dating for moms.” I took the chance and joined and to my pleasant surprise I was met by so many women who were going through the same things as I was, and most of them lived minutes away from me! I feel like Peanut should be a resource that it is talked more about even in the medical world considering how many appointments we have to go through in pregnancy.
